				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: WOO!!  Bards a Broke (Again)<a name="72225"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jan 20 05 2:44 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Yep, I have found that as well.  I don't mind it really, as I can just hit my hotbutton number &quot;1&quot; at any time, and then tap an alternate spell gem casting button, to turn off songs completely.  For clarity, see below:
<br />

<br />

<br />
For most situations, I have the following Song line up in my spell gems:
<br />

<br />
1.  Mez
<br />
2.  Mana song
<br />
3.  Psalm
<br />
4.  HoS
<br />
5.  Group haste (or AE resist if raiding)
<br />
6.  RoT
<br />
7.  Snare/slow (or invis, if travelling)
<br />
8.  Selos
<br />
9.  Kazumi's Note of Preservation (for when I actually get snared)
<br />

<br />
So, my hotbuttons are activated from the numberpad, and go like this:
<br />

<br />
1: /melody stop
<br />
    /cast 1
<br />

<br />
2: /melody stop
<br />
    /cast 2
<br />

<br />
3:  /melody stop
<br />
    /melody 3 5 2
<br />

<br />
4:  /melody stop
<br />
     /melody 4 5 2 3
<br />

<br />
5:  /melody stop
<br />
    /cast 5
<br />

<br />
6:  /melody stop
<br />
    /melody 4 6 7        (I use this for pulling, HoS, Slow, and Snare if needed, if not, I just go to hotbutton 3)
<br />

<br />
7:  /melody stop
<br />
     /cast 7
<br />

<br />
8:   /melody stop
<br />
     /cast 8
<br />

<br />
9:  /alt act 357  (bellow)
<br />
    /g INC &lt;&lt; %T &gt;&gt;
<br />
    /rs INC &lt;&lt; %T &gt;&gt;
<br />

<br />
10:  /melody stop (for some pulls, I delete this line)
<br />
      /attack off
<br />
      /alt act 212
<br />
     /g FADING, Wait for my call to heal!
<br />

<br />

<br />
For casting Kazumi's I use my alternate key, which is the number &quot;9&quot; on the keyboard, and just tap it twice.  I use it so seldom, that I don't mind doing it this tricky way.
<br />

<br />
So, as you can see, I've found ways to use /melody, without becoming crippled by it.  In most cases, I can still twist in the same way I did, I've just set up a few alternate shortcuts for when I'm running and talking, etc.  Like Number 3 hotbutton, I can hit the button, and let it run it's melody course, or I can interrupt to do a different sequence after the first song takes effect.
<br />

<br />
Hope this gave some of you idea's on how to integrate melody, and still retain control of your repertoire.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
